#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:12
msgid ""
"``pytest`` is a framework that makes building simple and scalable tests "
"easy. Tests are expressive and readable—no boilerplate code required. Get "
"started in minutes with a small unit test or complex functional test for "
"your application or library."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:18
msgid "Install ``pytest``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:20
msgid "Run the following command in your command line:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:22
msgid "pip install -U pytest"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:26
msgid "Check that you installed the correct version:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:28
msgid ""
"$ pytest --version\n"
"pytest 6.2.5"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:36
msgid "Create your first test"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:38
msgid "Create a simple test function with just four lines of code:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:40
msgid ""
"# content of test_sample.py\n"
"def func(x):\n"
"    return x + 1\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def test_answer():\n"
"    assert func(3) == 5"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:50
msgid "That’s it. You can now execute the test function:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:52
msgid ""
"$ pytest\n"
"=========================== test session starts "
"============================\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.x.y, pytest-6.x.y, py-1.x.y, pluggy-1.x.y\n"
"cachedir: $PYTHON_PREFIX/.pytest_cache\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR\n"
"collected 1 item\n"
"\n"
"test_sample.py F                                                     [100%]\n"
"\n"
"================================= FAILURES "
"=================================\n"
"_______________________________ test_answer "
"________________________________\n"
"\n"
"    def test_answer():\n"
">       assert func(3) == 5\n"
"E       assert 4 == 5\n"
"E        +  where 4 = func(3)\n"
"\n"
"test_sample.py:6: AssertionError\n"
"========================= short test summary info "
"==========================\n"
"FAILED test_sample.py::test_answer - assert 4 == 5\n"
"============================ 1 failed in 0.12s ============================="
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:76
msgid ""
"The ``[100%]`` refers to the overall progress of running all test cases. "
"After it finishes, pytest then shows a failure report because ``func(3)`` "
"does not return ``5``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:80
msgid ""
"You can use the ``assert`` statement to verify test expectations. pytest’s "
"`Advanced assertion introspection <http://docs.python.org/reference/"
"simple_stmts.html#the-assert-statement>`_ will intelligently report "
"intermediate values of the assert expression so you can avoid the many names "
"`of JUnit legacy methods <http://docs.python.org/library/unittest.html#test-"
"cases>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:83
msgid "Run multiple tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:85
msgid ""
"``pytest`` will run all files of the form test_*.py or \\*_test.py in the "
"current directory and its subdirectories. More generally, it follows :ref:"
"`standard test discovery rules <test discovery>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:89
msgid "Assert that a certain exception is raised"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:91
msgid ""
"Use the :ref:`raises <assertraises>` helper to assert that some code raises "
"an exception:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:93
msgid ""
"# content of test_sysexit.py\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def f():\n"
"    raise SystemExit(1)\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def test_mytest():\n"
"    with pytest.raises(SystemExit):\n"
"        f()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:107
msgid "Execute the test function with “quiet” reporting mode:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:109
msgid ""
"$ pytest -q test_sysexit.py\n"
".                                                                    [100%]\n"
"1 passed in 0.12s"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:117
msgid ""
"The ``-q/--quiet`` flag keeps the output brief in this and following "
"examples."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:120
msgid "Group multiple tests in a class"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:124
msgid ""
"Once you develop multiple tests, you may want to group them into a class. "
"pytest makes it easy to create a class containing more than one test:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:126
msgid ""
"# content of test_class.py\n"
"class TestClass:\n"
"    def test_one(self):\n"
"        x = \"this\"\n"
"        assert \"h\" in x\n"
"\n"
"    def test_two(self):\n"
"        x = \"hello\"\n"
"        assert hasattr(x, \"check\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:138
msgid ""
"``pytest`` discovers all tests following its :ref:`Conventions for Python "
"test discovery <test discovery>`, so it finds both ``test_`` prefixed "
"functions. There is no need to subclass anything, but make sure to prefix "
"your class with ``Test`` otherwise the class will be skipped. We can simply "
"run the module by passing its filename:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:140
msgid ""
"$ pytest -q test_class.py\n"
".F                                                                   [100%]\n"
"================================= FAILURES "
"=================================\n"
"____________________________ TestClass.test_two "
"____________________________\n"
"\n"
"self = <test_class.TestClass object at 0xdeadbeef>\n"
"\n"
"    def test_two(self):\n"
"        x = \"hello\"\n"
">       assert hasattr(x, \"check\")\n"
"E       AssertionError: assert False\n"
"E        +  where False = hasattr('hello', 'check')\n"
"\n"
"test_class.py:8: AssertionError\n"
"========================= short test summary info "
"==========================\n"
"FAILED test_class.py::TestClass::test_two - AssertionError: assert False\n"
"1 failed, 1 passed in 0.12s"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:160
msgid ""
"The first test passed and the second failed. You can easily see the "
"intermediate values in the assertion to help you understand the reason for "
"the failure."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:162
msgid "Grouping tests in classes can be beneficial for the following reasons:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:164
msgid "Test organization"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:165
msgid "Sharing fixtures for tests only in that particular class"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:166
msgid ""
"Applying marks at the class level and having them implicitly apply to all "
"tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:168
msgid ""
"Something to be aware of when grouping tests inside classes is that each "
"test has a unique instance of the class. Having each test share the same "
"class instance would be very detrimental to test isolation and would promote "
"poor test practices. This is outlined below:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:174
msgid ""
"# content of test_class_demo.py\n"
"class TestClassDemoInstance:\n"
"    def test_one(self):\n"
"        assert 0\n"
"\n"
"    def test_two(self):\n"
"        assert 0"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:185
msgid ""
"$ pytest -k TestClassDemoInstance -q\n"
"FF                                                                   [100%]\n"
"================================= FAILURES "
"=================================\n"
"______________________ TestClassDemoInstance.test_one "
"______________________\n"
"\n"
"self = <test_class_demo.TestClassDemoInstance object at 0xdeadbeef>\n"
"\n"
"    def test_one(self):\n"
">       assert 0\n"
"E       assert 0\n"
"\n"
"test_class_demo.py:3: AssertionError\n"
"______________________ TestClassDemoInstance.test_two "
"______________________\n"
"\n"
"self = <test_class_demo.TestClassDemoInstance object at 0xdeadbeef>\n"
"\n"
"    def test_two(self):\n"
">       assert 0\n"
"E       assert 0\n"
"\n"
"test_class_demo.py:6: AssertionError\n"
"========================= short test summary info "
"==========================\n"
"FAILED test_class_demo.py::TestClassDemoInstance::test_one - assert 0\n"
"FAILED test_class_demo.py::TestClassDemoInstance::test_two - assert 0\n"
"2 failed in 0.12s"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:214
msgid "Request a unique temporary directory for functional tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:216
msgid ""
"``pytest`` provides `Builtin fixtures/function arguments <https://docs."
"pytest.org/en/stable/builtin.html>`_ to request arbitrary resources, like a "
"unique temporary directory:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:218
msgid ""
"# content of test_tmpdir.py\n"
"def test_needsfiles(tmpdir):\n"
"    print(tmpdir)\n"
"    assert 0"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:225
msgid ""
"List the name ``tmpdir`` in the test function signature and ``pytest`` will "
"lookup and call a fixture factory to create the resource before performing "
"the test function call. Before the test runs, ``pytest`` creates a unique-"
"per-test-invocation temporary directory:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:227
msgid ""
"$ pytest -q test_tmpdir.py\n"
"F                                                                    [100%]\n"
"================================= FAILURES "
"=================================\n"
"_____________________________ test_needsfiles "
"______________________________\n"
"\n"
"tmpdir = local('PYTEST_TMPDIR/test_needsfiles0')\n"
"\n"
"    def test_needsfiles(tmpdir):\n"
"        print(tmpdir)\n"
">       assert 0\n"
"E       assert 0\n"
"\n"
"test_tmpdir.py:3: AssertionError\n"
"--------------------------- Captured stdout call "
"---------------------------\n"
"PYTEST_TMPDIR/test_needsfiles0\n"
"========================= short test summary info "
"==========================\n"
"FAILED test_tmpdir.py::test_needsfiles - assert 0\n"
"1 failed in 0.12s"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:248
msgid ""
"More info on tmpdir handling is available at :ref:`Temporary directories and "
"files <tmpdir handling>`."
msgstr ""

